explanation.body:
Note: For part iii, a counterexample is A = $ \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0  \\
0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 \\ 
\end{bmatrix}  $. $A^T$ is then $ \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0 
\end{bmatrix}  $

By rank nullity theorem, the nullity of A is 2 (# of columns) - 1 (rank) = 1.  The nullity of $A^T$ is 3 - 1 = 2. Clearly the dimension of the nullspace for these two matrices is not the same. Thus, iii is not correct.

The video has an error despite obtaining the same answer.

The row reduction should be R3 = R3 - 3*R1, not R3 = R3 - 2*R1. This means that the resulting matrix after the two row reduction steps (second line) should be:

$
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}1 & 2 & 2 & 0 \\ c-2 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & c-6 & 0 & 0 \end{array}\right]
$

Here, it is then clear that for $c=2$ , this matrix reduces to

$
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}1 & 2 & 2 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & -4 & 0 & 0 \end{array}\right] -> \left[\begin{array}{cccc}1 & 0 & 2 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \end{array}\right]
$

which has one free variable (the third column). This corresponds to a nullity of 1. The same goes for  $c=6$ . The matrix reduces to:

$
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}1 & 0 & 2 & 0 \\ 4 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \end{array}\right] ->
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}0 & 1 & 1 & 0 \\ 1 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \end{array}\right] 
$

with row reduction. Again, this system has one free variable (the third column), corresponding to a nullity of 1. 

The answer is E.

The video explanation of 11a is incorrect. The row reduction is fine but the solution should be 

$
\mathbf{x} = \left[\begin{array}{cccc} 3/2 \\ 13/2  \\ 1/2 \\1 \end{array}\right] t
$
The nullspace is spanned by the spanning vector $ \left[\begin{array}{cccc} 3/2 \\ 13/2  \\ 1/2 \\1 \end{array}\right] $. 
The zero vector is within the nullspace- it is obtained by multiplying the above spanning vector by a constant 0. 

The nullspace is not a subspace of R3 because elements in the nullspace have 4 elements whereas elements in R3 only have 3. This does not make sense so a is incorrect. 

The explanations for B, C, D, E still stand, just recognize that the expression I wrote for $\mathbf{x}$ in the video is incorrect. 

Side note: The nullspace is a subspace of R4. It satisfies all the requirements (you can check the last two yourself): 1). includes 0 vector, 2). any two elements in the nullspace when added together yields an element still in the nullspace, 3). any element in the nullspace multiplied by a scalar is still an element in the nullspace.

Note: In the video, I showed a counterexample that had repeated eigenvalues, so it does not apply to the (ii) statement. The actual reasoning for this is that only real, symmetric matrices with distinct eigenvalues have orthogonal eigenvectors. There are real matrices with distinct eigenvalues that don't have orthogonal eigenvectors (play around with some numbers and you'll find this).
The video has accidentally circled the wrong answer but the work is correct and matches the answer here.
There is a typo in the last step of the video explanation. The last basis vector should be [-4 0 -1 0 1].
